Differing Concentration of AirBnb locations and Effect of Nightly Rate on Multiple Variables

Edward Chang, Ben Draper, Joanne (In Sol) Jun, David Smith

May 7, 2019

Introduction

In this project, we will perform an exploratory data analysis, followed by a formal data analysis into one of the fastest growing companies in the world - AirBnb. The company allows customers to give ratings of properties and these ratings help other potential customers choose where to stay. By analyzing data from separate areas (San Francisco and Oakland), we will explore how customer ratings are affected by different neighborhoods. It can be shown that some neighborhoods have higher ratings than other neighborhoods, for properties which are very similar. Moreover, we will show that different forms of property have certain impacts on customer ratings. Moving on this this, we will demonstrate the impact of nightly rate on customer rating. Rates vary between $20 to $2000, depending on the neighborhood and the property. This variation in data allows us to explore the connection between variables, such as customer rating, and draw conclusions based around this.

Description of Data

This AirBnb data set records the city, neighborhood, property type, latitude, longitude, max occupancy, number of bathrooms, number of bedrooms, nightly rate, number of reviews, and average review score for 2992 listings. There are a total of 2158 listings located in 36 neighborhoods in San Francisco and 834 listings located in 106 neighborhoods in Oakland in this data set.
In a quick glance at the data, the listings vary greatly in their neighborhoods, the maximum number of listings in one neighborhood is 199 in the neighborhood named Mission. While there are a few similar counts of listings in other neighborhood, 48 neighborhoods have 4 or less listings with 20 of those having exactly 1 listing. This great variance in neighborhoods creates complication for accurate comparison between neighborhoods. The count of property types also suffers the same type of complication; there are 3 property types with only 1 observation, meanwhile the most numerous are the houses with a count of 644 and guest suites with a count of 406.
Aside from these qualitative observations, the number of reviews and average review scores do not appear to be reliable observations to use. The reason for this is because of their dependence on how long each listing has been operational; for listings that were recently posted for availability, they will have a lesser number of reviews and also have a rating different from if they were operational for much longer.
The other observations are quantitative and do not seem to present any complications.

#Topic 1: Distribution of AirBnb Listings

## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=37.786526,-122.319571&zoom=11&size=640x640&scale=4&maptype=terrain&key=xxx

Based on the first map of the locations of the listings in this data set, the density of listings in San Francisco is considerably higher than that of Oaklands. There seems to be less spread in the distribution of listings in San Francisco and this may be due to the preferred neighborhoods of AirBnb customers influencing an owners choice to start a listing. In Oakland, it appears that the latter also applies, however, there is a larger spread of listings; there are some areas of high concentration, however the majority of locations seem to be in various spots.

In the second map, the concentration of the listings seem to correspond to that of the previous map. (Although we do not have an exact number of bookings for each listing, the assumption that the number of reviews is proportional to the number of bookings is being used for this analysis.) This visual seems to provide evidence that there are preferred locations without regard to the problem with each listings length of operation. Ignoring that problem, removing the lesser booked listings eliminates some probability of the distributions of the listing just happening to be concentrated in those areas; there is now a visualization that there is more demand for listings in those areas because they have more reviews.

The centers of listing concentration for based on the two maps seem to be similar to each other, supporting that that there is a greater demand for listings in those specific neighborhoods or areas. To further this conclusion that the distribution is not random, a chi squared goodness of fitness test based on the frequency of listings per neighborhood will be performed (doing this per neighborhood provides a basis for grouping of listings).

Chi Squared Goodness of Fit Test on the Frequency of listings per neighborhood

A chi squared goodness of fit test will be able to conclude if the frequency of listings per neighborhood is due to chance or if some other factor is affecting it. To perform this test, we will proceed with two hypotheses:
The null hypothesis that the frequency of the listings per neighborhood is due to chance and that they are distributed equally, and the alternative hypothesis that the frequency of the listings per neighborhood is not due to chance and that they are not distributed equally. The p-value for such a hypothesis test is:

## [1] Using chisq.test method:
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  neighborhoodobs
## X-squared = 7932.9, df = 138, p-value < 2.2e-16
## [1] Using self-defined/textbook method:
## [1] X-squared = 7932.87967914439 ,df = 138 ,p-value = 0

Since obtained p-value is close to 0, we reject the null hypothesis, therefore we have extremely significant evidence that the frequency of listings per neighborhood is not due to chance and that the listings are not distributed equally. The neighborhoods themselves and some other variables might be affecting the listings neighborhood distributions.
To analyze these, analyzing other variables relationship to the neighborhoods will provide some further insight into what is correlated with or affecting the listing distribution.

Chi Squared Goodness of Fit Test on the count of unique neighborhoods per city

Another chi squared goodness of fit test will be performed to determine if the count of unique neighborhoods per city containing listings is due to chance. This test will use the following hypotheses:
the null hypothesis that the count of unique neighborhoods per city is due to chance, each city has the same count of unique neighborhoods, and that the city has no effect on the count of unique neighborhoods; and
the alternative hypothesis that the count of unique neighborhoods per city is not due to chance, the count of unique neighborhoods is not the same in the cities, and that the city or some other variable has an effect on the count of unique neighborhoods.

## [1] Using chisq.test method:
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  city_counts
## X-squared = 34.507, df = 1, p-value = 4.247e-09
## [1] Using self-defined/textbook method:
## [1] X-squared = 34.5070422535211 ,df = 1 ,p-value = 4.24711942504783e-09

Since our p-value = 4.237 x 10^-9 is close to 0, we reject the null hypothesis, therefore there is extremely significant evidence that the count of unique neighborhoods containing listings is not due to chance and not equal per city; and that the city or something else has an effect on the count of unique neighborhoods containing listings. Further analysis on other variables can be done to determine the correlation or effect of other specific variables on the distribution of listings.

Edward Chang (plots and descriptions for topic 1)

This bar graph plots the number of bedrooms against the total number of reviews that such listings have received. The graph is right skewed and spikes at 1, indicating that the a majority of customers book listings with 0, 1, or 2 bedroom(s). This means that there is a greater demand for listings with these amount of bedrooms. The areas with great concentration of listings should have bedrooms with such numbers. To check this, a map can be plotted, filtering the listings by 0, 1, or 2 bedrooms(s) and compare this with a plot of the rest of the bedroom counts.
This filtering of bedrooms in Maps 3 and 4 visualizes the drastic change in centers of concentration. In Map 3, the centers of concentration are very similar to that of Map 1s, which indicates that there was a strong influence of 0, 1, or 2 bedroom listings on the distribution of listings. On the other hand, Map 4s centers of concentrations are slightly off in San Francisco and very inaccurate in Oakland. As we can see from these maps, the number of bedrooms is related to the distribution of listings.

Topic 2: Effects of Nighly Rate on Multiple Variables

After plotting the regression lines of nightly rate vs.average review score for San Francisco, Oakland, and combined data, we observed that combined and SF data had positive slopes whereas Oakland data had slightly negative slope. Due to peoples tendency to pick listings with high rating and low nightly rate, top left corner of all three plots were concentrated. Moreover, because of this reason, the regression line for these plots are not accurate due to the skewed data.

Joanne (In Sol) Jun (Plot and Description for Topic 2)

For individual project, I chose to plot two data from Oakland and San Francisco to see differing trend of average review scores based of the nightly rate of apartments between two cities. This plot was particularly interesting to me that as nightly rate of apartments increase, the average review score for San Francisco tend to increase, whereas score for Oakland decreased. I believe that this shows how people tend to have high expectation for the apartments with high nightly rates for both cities; however, listings in Oakland with high nightly rate do not seem to fulfill those expectations. The limitation of this plot was that review scores of the listings in Oakland with high nightly rates lack which didnt sufficiently supported the regression line.

Houses in San Francisco may have a higher review score because of their proximity to one of the biggest tourist cities in the World. This shows that location does have an impact on reviews given to houses on AirBnb.

Since we obtained p-values of 1.93e-11 for combined data and 6.646e-14 for SF data which both considered as zero, we reject the null hypothesis that slope of the regression line made from the relationship between nightly rate and average review score is zero, and the relationship between the two variables is due to chance. With the strong evidence based on the hypothesis test and the regression lines on the plot, we concluded that the slope of the regression line for combined and SF data is positive (not zero). On the other hand, p-value for Oakland data was 0.2695 which we cannot reject the null hypothesis. To analyze deeper why the null hypothesis was rejected for the combined and SF data, we plotted the nightly rate vs.average rating score regression graphs based on property type and neighborhood.

#Conclusion Our two topics have allowed us to study the AirBnb market for San Francisco and Oakland, from our findings, we can draw on several conclusions. Firstly, topic 1 clearly showed that the frequency and distribution of listings in San Francisco and Oakland cannot be explained by chance. This rejects the null hypothesis and proves that in popular cities there will be a higher number of listings. This could be explained by the fact that San Francisco has world famous landmarks such as Alcatraz, which makes the city more popular with tourists who are not from California. Tourism could be one potential reason why there are more apartments in San Francisco and these apartments have a higher nightly rate in comparison to similar apartments in Oakland. Another reason for this, could be the increase in business activity between San Francisco and Oakland (see Reference 1). The figures show that San Francisco has 24% of its population working in management, business and finance, compared to 16.7% in Oakland. From topic 2, we can see the difference between the slope of the regression lines between the two cities. We found that while San Francisco has a positive slope, and rejects the null hypothesis, Oakland has a negative slope and does not reject the null hypothesis. Number of reviews does not change for the nightly rate in San Francisco, but there is a slightly decreasing pattern as the nightly rate increases in Oakland. This shows that whilst Oakland and San Francisco are geographically close, the market for listings are completely separate!
